Access to Government Benefits through the Nonprofit Sector

Kevin Schachter
Graduate Student, University of Manitoba

The Problem:
Benefit Non-take-up

Government Benefits Are Critical for Poverty Relief

  • 57.6 percent of total income for Canadian residents in the bottom income decile came from government transfers
  • Income benefits are prominent in Canada’s First Poverty Reduction Strategy
    • Canada Child Benefit
    • Guaranteed Income Supplement
    • Canada Workers Benefit

Source: Statistics Canada, 2016 Census of Population, Statistics Canada Catalogue no. 98-400-X2016116.

Many Low-income Canadians Miss Out on Benefits

  • 13.7 percent of people aged 15 and over in the bottom income decile did not receive any government transfers
  • 4 percent of households in the bottom income decile did not receive any government transfers

Source: Statistics Canada, 2016 Census of Population, Statistics Canada Catalogue nos. 98-400-X2016116 and 98-400-X2016146.

Benefit Take-up Is Complicated

Accessing government benefits may require:

  • Personal income tax filing
  • Separate applications (paper or online)
  • In-person meetings
  • Documentation and personal identification
  • Personal income tax filing
  • Paper applications
  • Online applications
  • In-person intake meetings
  • Documentation and personal identification to prove eligibility
  • Appeals to adjudicatory panels if benefit claims are denied

The Program:
Benefit Intermediary Services

  • Nonprofit organizations and arms-length agencies assist low-income Canadians to claim their benefits.
  • Nonprofit organizations have worked to address this issue by offering programs that assist vulnerable community members in filing income tax returns and claiming government benefits.

Case Study:
Benefit Intermediaries in Winnipeg

This paper presents the methodology and findings of an applied case study of nonprofit benefit intermediary programs in Winnipeg.

Research Questions

  1. How do benefit intermediary programs promote access to government income benefits in Manitoba?
  2. What factors contribute to successful program outcomes?
  3. What constraints do these programs face?

Methodology

Realist Analysis

Ray Pawson, “Theorizing the Interview,” The British Journal of Sociology 47, no. 2 (1996): 295–314, doi:10.2307/591728; Ray Pawson and Nick Tilley, Realistic Evaluation (Thousand Oaks, CA: SAGE Publications Inc., 1997).

  • Draw upon Pawson and Tilley’s Realistic Evaluation
  • Realistic evaluation asks
    • “why a program works for whom and in what circumstances.” (Pawson and Tilley 1997, xvi)
  • Without delving too deep into methodology, realist evaluation attempts to explain social patterns by focusing on:
    • the context in which a social program takes place
    • the mechanisms for change triggered by a program
    • program outcomes (desired and realized)

Insider Research

This research is both applied and academic. - I am a practitioner - I am a researcher

Methods

  • Semi-structured interviews with six key informants
  • Review of scholarly and grey literature
  • Statistics Canada data tables

Findings

Findings from document analysis and semi-structured stakeholder interviews demonstrate that these programs seek to increase benefit take-up by providing individual support to vulnerable community members, and to effect systemic changes that increase benefit accessibility.

Public and Private Supports Are Lacking

Public Sector

  • “Bureaucratic disentitlement”
  • Closure of in-person help desks
  • Insufficient call centre capacity
  • Offloading to community

Private Sector

  • May be too costly
  • Often don’t specialize in benefits available to low-income community members

Michael Lipsky, “Bureaucratic Disentitlement in Social Welfare Programs,” Social Service Review 58, no. 1 (March 1, 1984): 3–27, doi:10.1086/644161.

  • Many low-income Canadians face barriers to accessing government income benefits that are integral to meeting their basic needs.
  • Many vulnerable community members face difficulties:
    • Completing the application processes required to obtain these benefits.
    • Accessing appropriate support from the public and private sectors.
  • Limited public support:
    • “bureaucratic disentitlement”
    • Closure of CRA Tax Services Offices to public enquiries
    • Call volumes at CRA and Service Canada call centres
    • Retrenchment of CVITP coordination, training, and supports.

Benefit Intermediaries (Partially) Fill This Gap

  • Nonprofit organizations and arms-length agencies mediate access to income benefits (affirmation) and work for systemic changes to increase benefit accessibility (nonreformist reform).

Nancy Fraser, “Social Justice in the Age of Identity Politics: Redistribution, Recognition, and Participation,” in Redistribution or Recognition? A Political-Philosophical Exchange, by Nancy Fraser and Axel Honneth (New York: Verso, 2003), 7–109.

Affirmation

Affirmation: Goals

Redistribution

  • Benefit intermediaries increase service users’ incomes and enhance quality of life.

Recognition

  • Benefit intermediaries empower service users to interact with the welfare state from a position of higher status.

Fraser, “Social Justice in the Age of Identity Politics: Redistribution, Recognition, and Participation.”

Source: Fraser (1997)

Affirmation: Activities

  • Financial literacy education and public legal education
  • Benefit screening
  • Tax return preparation and benefit applications
  • Financial problem-solving and coaching
  • Advocacy and representation

Affirmation: Outcomes

Redistribution

6 organizations served about 14,000 service users who accessed $38 million of government income benefits in 2018.

Recognition

  • Greater knowledge and awareness
  • Reduced stress
  • Enhanced skills and confidence

The income support piece is important. … I like to think of it as, it stops the bleeding. It prevents people from falling further into the abyss.

Affirmation: Key Mechanisms

  • Services match community needs
    • Government transfers are important
    • Few options for benefits assistance
    • Benefit intermediaries offer free support
    • Community members trust community service providers
  • A recognitive approach to redistribution
    • “Taking the lead from the participant”
    • “Supportive counseling”

I’m not going to say we’re social workers or anything, but part of the job is – you have to have the ability to listen and let each person know that they’re important. They matter. And that they’re not just another number.

Nonreformist Reform

Nonreformist Reform: Goals

  • to eliminate structural barriers that inhibit benefit take-up
  • to build cross-sectoral capacity to assist low-income community members to access their benefits

Immediate Outcome

  • Enhance service users’ quality of life.

Long-term Impact

  • Increase the accessibility of welfare state income benefits.

Source: Fraser (2003)

Nonreformist Reform: Activities

  • Direct service delivery
  • Cross-sectoral collaboration
  • Public policy advocacy
  • Contention: complaints & litigation
  • Observe systemic patterns and amplify service users’ voices
  • Collaborate with policymakers, public servants, and “street-level bureaucrats” to change policy and practice
  • Train other agencies to screen for and support access to benefits
  • Challenge benefits legislation and regulations through litigation and ombudsman complaints

Nonreformist Reform: Observed Outcomes

  • Changes to benefit eligibility criteria, regulations, policies, and practices
  • Increased investment in public sector and nonprofit benefit assistance services
  • A growing field of practice: a “tax empire”

One organization built a “tax empire” to meet community need.

Each year they…

  • Recruit and train 100 volunteers
  • A dozen training sessions
  • Procure and set up computers, software, internet, and phone
  • Manage 7 volunteer income tax clinics
  • Support 26 other agencies that prepare tax returns

Well, as soon as we smash capitalism, right, but until then [laughs], I think you can have a big effect by having people who work within those systems have a better understanding of the people who rely on those systems. One piece of it is doing what we can to help people working within those systems operate from a strengths-based approach – what can they do to not just be a needless bureaucracy.

Nonreformist Reform: Key Mechanisms

  • Flexible framing
    • Social justice
    • Cost reduction / return on investment
  • Learning from service users
    • Noticing patterns through service delivery
    • Bringing systemic issues to policymakers, politicians, and partners

This is costly to our system, and so if you don’t believe me that it’s the right thing to do, I’m also going to tell you that this could actually save money.

The social policy work that we do, that nonprofits do, is really important. Because we have this great resource that governments can learn a great deal from, and that’s our clients.

Constraints

“Voluntary Failure”

  • “philanthropic insufficiency”
    • not enough resources to meet community need
  • “philanthropic paternalism”
    • reliance on state funding limits public policy engagement
  • “philanthropic particularism”
    • agencies may target specific demographics, regions, or time periods

Lester M. Salamon, “Of Market Failure, Voluntary Failure, and Third-Party Government: Toward a Theory of Government-Nonprofit Relations in the Modern Welfare State,” Nonprofit and Voluntary Sector Quarterly 16, no. 1–2 (January 1, 1987): 29–49, doi:10.1177/089976408701600104.

Source: Salamon (1987)

The big disadvantage is that we can only be a drop in the bucket. People have to line up. We’ve tried to minimize the impact of people having to navigate our waiting lists and whatever. But it’s still a big hassle for people to have to compete for scarce space with us.

Benefit Intermediaries Are Part of The “Shadow State”

  • They redistribute income by mediating access to welfare state income benefits
  • They deliver services that were offloaded from the welfare state
  • They rely on state funding to deliver services

Jennifer Wolch, “The Shadow State : Transformations in the Voluntary Sector,” in The Power of Geography: How Territory Shapes Social Life, ed. Jennifer R. Wolch and Michael J. Dear (Boston: Unwin Hyman, 1989), 197–221.

“a para-state apparatus with collective service responsibilities previously shouldered by the public sector, administered outside democratic politics, but yet controlled in both formal and informal ways by the state.” (Wolch 1989:201)

Nonprofits face challenges to achieving these impacts: - If government benefits are inadequate, then mediated redistribution will not be either. - Tweddle and Aldridge (2018) – welfare incomes as low as 52% of the MBM for Winnipeg. - They lack the resources required to fully meet community needs - They must be cautious in advocating for systemic changes given their reliance on government funding. - Channeling low-income community members through benefit intermediaries may lead to system stasis and stigmatization

I think it also takes people out of the mainstream. So people are having this sort of particular experience of interacting with big parts of systems that’s like, ‘Oh, this how poor people do this. And this is how everybody else does their taxes.’ … And so I think it’s sort of a disservice. Systems don’t have to adapt to low-income people’s needs if we’re taking on all that.

Summary

This paper contributes to research and practice by articulating the limited, yet integral role played by nonprofit access to benefits programs, outlining constraints faced by agencies engaged in this work, and highlighting promising practices that can increase benefit take-up.

Benefit Intermediaries

  • affirm service users access to welfare state income benefits
    (redistribution)
  • provide opportunities for service users to build esteem
    (recognition)
  • pursue systemic changes to increase benefit accessibility
    (nonreformist reform)
  • face contextual constraints that limit their impact
  • Benefit intermediaries contribute towards redressing socioeconomic injustice and increase service user’s quality of life.
